gmd:abstract.gco:CharacterString: This point data layer represents addresses for Taylor County, Wisconsin at year-end 2016. It is a feature class within the geodatabase 'Taylor_Addresses_YE2016.gdb'. [Buildings represent a collection of points spatially located over the main building for any given address. For the most part, in urban areas, there is not a building point located unless the main building would not be physically visible from the road. The data was developed to only show the main structure for a given address, meaning that there is only one building point per address . In the case of duplexes or multi family structures additional building points and site access points are added. By only having one building point per address and one site access point, a one to one relationship is maintained with the site access point.]

gmd:purpose.gco:CharacterString:
This layer is intended for reference and mapping purposes, and may be used for basic applications such as viewing, querying, and map output production, or to provide a basemap to support graphical overlays and analysis with other spatial data.
[This data set was created as a foundational element for Taylor County. The building feature class provides a digital representation of all primary buildings or structures within Vernon County and is to be used in conjunction with developed digital road centerline, site access points, and driveway feature classes. The building feature class is intended to be used to enhance addressing information within the County. It is a subset to the site access points.]

gmd:supplementalInformation.gco:CharacterString:
Augmented original metadata with UW-Madison specific elements.
This data was submitted to the UW geospatial archive in 2017. Content may be considered current as of December 31, 2016. It was published to the UW geospatial archive as part of the Wisconsin Department of Administration Land Information Program annual collection of public data for the year 2017.
[This data set was created as a foundational element for the Taylor County Land Information System. The building feature class provides a digital representation of all address building locations within Taylor County and is to be used in conjunction with developed digital road centerline, site access, and driveway feature classes. The building feature class was intended to be used to enhance addressing information within the County.]

gmd:measureDescription.gco:CharacterString: [All information has been checked for accuracy and is correct to the best of Taylor County's knowledge. Tests and checks for data include table analysis with the property tax listing, ANI/ALI and address maps. All points were placed based on the 2006 Orthophotography.]

[To the best knowledge of Taylor County, this data set includes all of the building points for Taylor County, Wisconsin. The data, however, is dynamic and therefore will be maintained and updated on a regular basis. Because of the dynamic nature of the data, the data should never be construed as complete.]
[All information has been checked for accuracy and is correct to the best of Taylor County's knowledge.]

[This data was developed by ADC utilizing 2006 aerial imagery with a 18-inch pixel resolution and 2005 NAIP imagery. The building point was placed on the main building shown on the aerial imagery. Buildings that were questionable on the imagery or not found on the imagery have been noted as so or represented by the site access point only.]
Attribute information remains the same as given by the author of the data.

[Step 1: Convert delivered address points shapefile to feature class. Cleaned out unneeded information and added additional necessary fields determined by the counties needs. At this point, domains were also created based on county standards.]

[Step 3: Attributed the building point with address or confirmed existing address from address points delivered. Also attributed unique information such as the parcel identification number with a attribute transfer. Unique address id was created in an automated process as points were created.]

[Step 7: Table was QC'ed for missing and incorrect data. This includes table analysis within itself and joined to the roads and site access tables. This ensures that the repetitive data remains consistent.]

[Step 6: All spatial attributes were assigned to the building points. This included information such as zip codes, ESN and MCD. All buildings along boundary lines were examined to ensure the correct number was assigned.]
[Step 5: The building point was copied to the site access layer.]
[Step 8: Metadata created.]

[Step 4: Missing addresses were searched for in the property tax database and ANI/ALI. Additional addresses were then created as described in steps 1-3. At this point, modifiers were also attributed in the addresses.]
